@David Eisenberg

A JOULE is the Système International unit of energy.  Work and heat are both forms of energy.  But energy is a "state function", meaning that a change in energy only depends on the initial and final state in any transformation path.  So lifting a kilogram one meter against earth gravity requires 9.8 joules.  But the amount amount of work it takes to lift it, and the amount of heat lost or gained while it is being lifted, depends on the way in which the object is lifted.

And as SP said, a watt is a unit of power, joules/sec, also an SI unit.

