@Jane Wheelaghan
"And sometimes Y and W" is part of the vowel progression...  Think of BY, SKY, THY (long Y) and baby, silly, toothy (short Y).
As for W,  in combination with A,E, or O, it forms a slightly different-sounding pair:  OWL EWE AWL ... phonics!

@MOL
There are a few instances of W used as a pure vowel, and not just a semi-vowel, mainly in words adopted directly from Welsh (but listed in M-W, etc.): "crwth," and "cwm." This last, church-goers are most likely to know from the hymn-tune name CWM RHONDDA, aka "Guide me, O Thou great Jehovah."
But rare enough, we should probably just leave it at "and sometimes Y."

